Cindy Sheehan questions President Bush on why her son died for a cause he called noble.
She demands answers and vows to continue her protest until she can confront him directly.
Despite her grief, Jim Boskovitch supports the Iraq military action, echoing his son's beliefs.
Sheehan's activism has gained attention, with anti-war groups urging Bush to meet her.
The White House officials met with Sheehan briefly but did not address her demands.
Sheehan's persistence has sparked a national debate on the war, drawing both support and criticism.
Her emotional plea for accountability resonates as she seeks closure and justice for her son's sacrifice
